# **Moving from Scarcity to Abundance**

My grandfather grew up on a farm during the great depression. At that time, you pinched pennies because you had to. You didn't have a choice. Survival meant saving every penny.

As a result, my father grew up in this penny-pinching environment. Although his perspective did change over time, the mindset of scarcity profoundly influenced him.

To a large degree, I adopted this same mindset growing up. However, when I got married, I stared my beliefs in the face, which forced me to reexamine my mindset.

I discovered no matter how much money I had in the bank, an underlying belief that "I don't have enough" always haunted me. 

I worried more, worked harder, and frustrated my poor wife because I could never make a financial decision without agonizing caution, hesitancy, and fear.

Such was my perspective of money.

## **Scarcity Will Persist as Long As You Let It**

Gradually, I changed my perspective to believe, "I will always have enough." 

You know what?

I've been in times much tougher, tighter, with more financial obligations and I've always found there to be enough. What’s more, I can live in those situations without fear or anxiety, because I know there is always enough. 

Now my financial decisions are being shaped intentionally rather than fearfully, which enables me to make better financial decisions.

Yet, this “abundance mindset” encompasses more than just having enough finances.

## **Abundance Makes Room for Everyone’s Success**

It also says there is always enough *room* for everyone.

As a young individual determined to make something of myself and change the world, I found myself increasingly jealous of others around me who were being promoted.

I had a flawed perspective: I believed every promotion given to someone else left fewer promotions for me. I thought we were all taking slices out of the same pie. I failed to realize that we were actually making the pie bigger.

That's the essence of generating wealth: *making the pie bigger.*

My scarcity mindset also kept me from being able to pursue my own potential. I hesitated because I feared it would block others from being who they truly wanted to be.

However, when my perspective changed, I began to celebrate other people's promotion. I was happy whether I received recognition or not.

How are you still influenced by a scarcity mindset, and how can you shift that into abundance thinking?
